[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions can help a programmer read the code, help a compiler compile it, or help the program detect its own defects.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] For the latter, some programs check assertions by actually evaluating the predicate as they run.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Then, if it is not in fact true – an assertion failure – the program considers itself to be broken and typically deliberately crashes or throws an assertion failure exception.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Programmers can use assertions to help specify programs and to reason about program correctness.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] For example, a precondition—an assertion placed at the beginning of a section of code—determines the set of states under which the programmer expects the code to execute.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] A postcondition—placed at the end—describes the expected state at the end of execution.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The example above uses the notation for including assertions used by C.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] That notation cannot be used in existing mainstream programming languages.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] However, programmers can include unchecked assertions using the comment feature of their programming language.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The braces included in the comment help distinguish this use of a comment from other uses.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Libraries may provide assertion features as well.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Several modern programming languages include checked assertions – statements that are checked at runtime or sometimes statically.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] If an assertion evaluates to false at runtime, an assertion failure results, which typically causes execution to abort.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This draws attention to the location at which the logical inconsistency is detected and can be preferable to the behaviour that would otherwise result.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The use of assertions helps the programmer design, develop, and reason about a program.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In languages such as Eiffel, assertions form part of the design process; other languages, such as C and Java, use them only to check assumptions at runtime.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In both cases, they can be checked for validity at runtime, but can usually also be suppressed.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions can function as a form of documentation: they can describe the state the code expects to find before it runs (its preconditions), and the state the code expects to result in when it is finished running (postconditions); they can also specify invariants of a class.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Eiffel integrates such assertions into the language and automatically extracts them to document the class.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This forms an important part of the method of design by contract.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This approach is also useful in languages that do not explicitly support it: the advantage of using assertion statements rather than assertions in comments is that the program can check the assertions every time it runs; if the assertion no longer holds, an error can be reported.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This prevents the code from getting out of sync with the assertions.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] For example, the following demonstrates design by contract in C++ (using C++26 contracts).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] An assertion may be used to verify that an assumption made by the programmer during the implementation of the program remains valid when the program is executed.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In Java, `%` is the *remainder* operator (*modulo*), and in Java, if its first operand is negative, the result can also be negative (unlike the modulo used in mathematics).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer has assumed that `total` is non-negative, so that the remainder of a division by 2 will always be 0 or 1.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The assertion makes this assumption explicit: if `countNumberOfUsers` does return a negative value, the program may have a bug.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] A major advantage of this technique is that when an error does occur, it is detected immediately and directly, rather than later through often obscure effects.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Since an assertion failure usually reports the code location, one can often pinpoint the error without further debugging.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions are also sometimes placed at points where the execution is not supposed to reach.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] For example, assertions could be placed at the `default` clause of the `switch` statement in languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Any case that the programmer does not handle intentionally will raise an error, and the program will abort rather than silently continuing in an erroneous state.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In D such an assertion is added automatically when a `switch` statement doesn't contain a `default` clause.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In Java, assertions have been a part of the language since version 1.4.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertion failures result in raising an `AssertionError` when the program is run with the appropriate flags, without which the assert statements are ignored.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In C, they are added on by the standard header `<assert.h>` defining `assert(*assertion*)` as a macro that signals an error in the case of failure, usually terminating the program.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In C++, both `<assert.h>` and `<cassert>` headers provide the `assert` macro.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The danger of assertions is that they may cause side effects either by changing memory data or by changing thread timing.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions should be implemented carefully, so they cause no side effects on program code.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertion constructs in a language allow for easy test-driven development (TDD) without the use of a third-party library.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In C#, there is no assertion macro or keyword, but instead classes `System.Diagnostics.Debug` and `System.Diagnostics.Trace` which provide `Assert()` methods.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] During the development cycle, the programmer will typically run the program with assertions enabled.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] When an assertion failure occurs, the programmer is immediately notified of the problem.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Many assertion implementations will also halt the program's execution: this is useful, since if the program continued to run after an assertion violation occurred, it might corrupt its state and make the cause of the problem more difficult to locate.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Using the information provided by the assertion failure (such as the location of the failure and perhaps a stack trace, or even the full program state if the environment supports core dumps or if the program is running in a debugger), the programmer can usually fix the problem.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Thus, assertions provide a very powerful tool in debugging.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] When a program is deployed to production, assertions are typically turned off to avoid any overhead or side effects they may have.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In some cases, assertions are completely absent from deployed code, such as in C/C++ assertions via macros.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In other cases, such as Java, assertions are present in the deployed code and can be turned on in the field for debugging.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions may also be used to promise the compiler that a given edge condition is not actually reachable, thereby permitting certain optimizations that would not otherwise be possible.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In this case, disabling the assertions could actually reduce performance.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions that are checked at compile time are called static assertions.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Static assertions are particularly useful in compile-time template metaprogramming, but can also be used in low-level languages like C by introducing illegal code if (and only if) the assertion fails.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] C11 and C++11 support static assertions directly through `static_assert`.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because the compiler will not allow two case labels with the same constant.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int)==4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This construct does not work at file scope (i.e., not inside a function), and so it must be wrapped inside a function.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because arrays may not have a negative length.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] If, in fact, the compiler allows a negative length, then the initialization byte (the `'!'` part) should cause even such over-lenient compilers to complain.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int) == 4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Both of these methods require a method of constructing unique names.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers support a `__COUNTER__` preprocessor define that facilitates the construction of unique names, by returning monotonically increasing numbers for each compilation unit.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] D provides static assertions through the use of `static assert`.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This might look like a smart way to assign the return value of `malloc` to `ptr` and check if it is `NULL` in one step, but the `malloc` call and the assignment to `ptr` is a side effect of evaluating the expression that forms the `assert` condition.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] When the `NDEBUG` parameter is passed to the compiler, as when the program is considered to be error-free and released, the `assert()` statement is removed, so `malloc()` isn't called, rendering `ptr` uninitialised.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] This could potentially result in a segmentation fault or similar null pointer error much further down the line in program execution, causing bugs that may be sporadic and/or difficult to track down.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Programmers sometimes use a similar VERIFY(X) define to alleviate this problem.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers may issue a warning when encountering the above code.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] Furthermore, we may, at such a point, indicate the validity of these limitations.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] The assertional method for proving the correctness of programs was advocated by Alan Turing.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In a talk "Checking a Large Routine" at Cambridge, June 24, 1949, Turing suggested: "How can one check a large routine in the sense of making sure that it's right?
[src:axiomatic-semantics/assertion-software-development] In order that the man who checks may not have too difficult a task, the programmer should make a number of definite *assertions* which can be checked individually, and from which the correctness of the whole program easily follows".
[src:axiomatic-semantics/axiomatic-semantics] Axiomatic semantics define the meaning of a command in a program by describing its effect on assertions about the program state.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/axiomatic-semantics] The assertions are logical statements—predicates with variables, where the variables define the state of the program.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] In theoretical computer science, an algorithm is **correct** with respect to a specification if it behaves as specified.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Best explored is *functional* correctness, which refers to the input–output behavior of the algorithm: for each input, it produces an output satisfying the specification.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Within the latter notion, *partial correctness*, requiring that *if* an answer is returned, it will be correct, is distinguished from *total correctness*, which additionally requires that an answer *is* eventually returned, i.e., the algorithm terminates.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Correspondingly, to prove a program's total correctness, it is sufficient to prove its partial correctness and its termination.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] The latter kind of proof (termination proof) can never be fully automated, since the halting problem is undecidable.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] For example, successively searching through the positive integers (1, 2, 3, …) to see if we can find an odd perfect number is quite easy to write and is a partially correct program that *would* find an odd perfect number, if such a number exists (see box).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] However, to say this program is totally correct (i.e., that it *will* find such a number and terminate) would be to assert that an odd perfect number actually exists, which is currently not known in number theory.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] A proof would have to be a mathematical proof, assuming both the algorithm and specification are given formally.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] In particular, it is not expected to be a correctness assertion for a given program implementing the algorithm on a given machine.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] That would involve such considerations as limitations on computer memory.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] A deep result in proof theory, the Curry–Howard correspondence, states that a proof of functional correctness in constructive logic corresponds to a certain program in the lambda calculus.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Converting a proof in this way is called *program extraction*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Hoare logic is a specific formal system for reasoning rigorously about the correctness of computer programs.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] It uses axiomatic techniques to define programming language semantics and argue about the correctness of programs through assertions known as Hoare triples.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Software testing is any activity aimed at evaluating an attribute or capability of a program or system and determining that it meets its required results.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Although crucial to software quality and widely deployed by programmers and testers, software testing still remains an art due to a limited understanding of the principles of software.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] The difficulty in software testing stems from the complexity of software: we can not completely test a program with moderate complexity.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] The purpose of testing can be quality assurance, verification and validation, or reliability estimation.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Testing can be used as a generic metric as well.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Correctness testing and reliability testing are two major areas of testing.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/correctness-computer-science] Software testing is a trade-off between budget, time, and quality.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] In the context of hardware and software systems, **formal verification** is the act of proving or disproving the correctness of a system with respect to a certain formal specification or property, using formal methods of mathematics.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Formal verification is a key incentive for formal specification of systems, and is at the core of formal methods.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] It represents an important dimension of analysis and verification in electronic design automation and is one approach to software verification.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The use of formal verification enables the highest Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL7) in the framework of common criteria for computer security certification.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Formal verification can be helpful in proving the correctness of systems such as: cryptographic protocols, combinational circuits, digital circuits with internal memory, and software expressed as source code in a programming language.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Prominent examples of verified software systems include the CompCert verified C compiler and the seL4 high-assurance operating system kernel.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The verification of these systems is done by ensuring the existence of a formal proof of a mathematical model of the system.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Model checking involves a systematic and exhaustive exploration of the mathematical model.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Such exploration is possible for finite models, but also for some infinite models, where infinite sets of states can be effectively represented finitely by using abstraction or taking advantage of symmetry.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Usually, this consists of exploring all states and transitions in the model, by using smart and domain-specific abstraction techniques to consider whole groups of states in a single operation and reduce computing time.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Implementation techniques include state space enumeration, symbolic state space enumeration, abstract interpretation, symbolic simulation, abstraction refinement.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The properties to be verified are often described in temporal logics, such as linear temporal logic (LTL), Property Specification Language (PSL), SystemVerilog Assertions (SVA), or computational tree logic (CTL).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Another approach is deductive verification.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Formal verification of software programs involves proving that a program satisfies a formal specification of its behavior.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Subareas of formal verification include deductive verification (see above), abstract interpretation, automated theorem proving, type systems, and lightweight formal methods.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] A promising type-based verification approach is dependently typed programming, in which the types of functions include (at least part of) those functions' specifications, and type-checking the code establishes its correctness against those specifications.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Fully featured dependently typed languages support deductive verification as a special case.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Another complementary approach is program derivation, in which efficient code is produced from functional specifications by a series of correctness-preserving steps.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] An example of this approach is the Bird–Meertens formalism, and this approach can be seen as another form of program synthesis.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] These techniques can be *sound*, meaning that the verified properties can be logically deduced from the semantics, or *unsound*, meaning that there is no such guarantee.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] A sound technique yields a result only once it has covered the entire space of possibilities.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] An example of an unsound technique is one that covers only a subset of the possibilities, for instance only integers up to a certain number, and give a "good-enough" result.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Techniques can also be *decidable*, meaning that their algorithmic implementations are guaranteed to terminate with an answer, or undecidable, meaning that they may never terminate.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] By bounding the scope of possibilities, unsound techniques that are decidable might be able to be constructed when no decidable sound techniques are available.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Verification is one aspect of testing a product's fitness for purpose.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Often one refers to the overall checking process as V & V.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The verification process consists of static/structural and dynamic/behavioral aspects.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] E.g., for a software product one can inspect the source code (static) and run against specific test cases (dynamic).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Validation usually can be done only dynamically, i.e., the product is tested by putting it through typical and atypical usages ("Does it satisfactorily meet all use cases?").
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Program repair is performed with respect to an oracle, encompassing the desired functionality of the program which is used for validation of the generated fix.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] A simple example is a test-suite—the input/output pairs specify the functionality of the program.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] A variety of techniques are employed, most notably using satisfiability modulo theories (SMT) solvers, and genetic programming, using evolutionary computing to generate and evaluate possible candidates for fixes.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The former method is deterministic, while the latter is randomized.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] For example, the Nopol tool encodes the repair of buggy conditional statements as an SMT instance to determinstically generate patches for if conditions and missing preconditions.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Program repair combines techniques from formal verification and program synthesis.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Fault-localization techniques in formal verification are used to compute program points which might be possible bug-locations, which can be targeted by the synthesis modules.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Repair systems often focus on a small pre-defined class of bugs in order to reduce the search space.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Industrial use is limited owing to the computational cost of existing techniques.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The growth in complexity of designs increases the importance of formal verification techniques in the hardware industry.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] At present, formal verification is used by most or all leading hardware companies, but its use in the software industry is still languishing.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] This could be attributed to the greater need in the hardware industry, where errors have greater commercial significance.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Because of the potential subtle interactions between components, it is increasingly difficult to exercise a realistic set of possibilities by simulation.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Important aspects of hardware design are amenable to automated proof methods, making formal verification easier to introduce and more productive.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] As of 2011, several operating systems have been formally verified: NICTA's Secure Embedded L4 microkernel, sold commercially as seL4 by OK Labs; OSEK/VDX based real-time operating system ORIENTAIS by East China Normal University; Green Hills Software's Integrity operating system; and SYSGO's PikeOS.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] In 2016, a team led by Zhong Shao at Yale developed a formally verified operating system kernel called CertiKOS.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] As of 2017, formal verification has been applied to the design of large computer networks through a mathematical model of the network, and as part of a new network technology category, intent-based networking.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] Network software vendors that offer formal verification solutions include Cisco Forward Networks and Veriflow Systems.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The SPARK programming language provides a toolset which enables software development with formal verification and is used in several high-integrity systems.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/formal-verification] The CompCert C compiler is a formally verified C compiler implementing the majority of ISO C.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] In computer science, a **loop invariant** is a property of a program loop that is true before (and after) each iteration.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] It is a logical assertion, sometimes checked with a code assertion.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Knowing its invariant(s) is essential in understanding the effect of a loop.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] In formal program verification, particularly the Floyd-Hoare approach, loop invariants are expressed by formal predicate logic and used to prove properties of loops and by extension algorithms that employ loops (usually correctness properties).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The loop invariants will be true on entry into a loop and following each iteration, so that on exit from the loop, both the loop invariants and the loop termination condition can be guaranteed.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] From a programming methodology viewpoint, the loop invariant can be viewed as a more abstract specification of the loop, which characterizes the deeper purpose of the loop beyond the details of this implementation.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] A survey article covers fundamental algorithms from many areas of computer science (searching, sorting, optimization, arithmetic etc.), characterizing each of them from the viewpoint of its invariant.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Because of the similarity of loops and recursive programs, proving partial correctness of loops with invariants is very similar to proving the correctness of recursive programs via induction.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] In fact, the loop invariant is often the same as the inductive hypothesis to be proved for a recursive program equivalent to a given loop.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The following C subroutine `max()` returns the maximum value in its argument array `a[]`, provided its length `n` is at least 1.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Comments are provided at lines 3, 6, 9, 11, and 13.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Each comment makes an assertion about the values of one or more variables at that stage of the function.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The highlighted assertions within the loop body, at the beginning and end of the loop (lines 6 and 11), are exactly the same.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] They thus describe an invariant property of the loop.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] When line 13 is reached, this invariant still holds, and it is known that the loop condition `i!=n` from line 5 has become false.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Both properties together imply that `m` equals the maximum value in `a[0...n-1]`, that is, that the correct value is returned from line 14.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Following a defensive programming paradigm, the loop condition `i!=n` in line 5 should better be modified to `i<n`, in order to avoid endless looping for illegitimate negative values of `n`.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] While this change in code intuitively shouldn't make a difference, the reasoning leading to its correctness becomes somewhat more complicated, since then only `i>=n` is known in line 13.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] In order to obtain that also `i<=n` holds, that condition has to be included in the loop invariant.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] It is easy to see that `i<=n`, too, is an invariant of the loop, since `i<n` in line 6 can be obtained from the (modified) loop condition in line 5, and hence `i<=n` holds in line 11 after `i` has been incremented in line 10.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] However, when loop invariants have to be manually provided for formal program verification, such intuitively too obvious properties like `i<=n` are often overlooked.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] In other words: The rule above is a deductive step that has as its premise the Hoare triple $\{C\land I\}\;\mathrm {body} \;\{I\}$ .
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] This triple is actually a relation on machine states.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] It holds whenever starting from a state in which the boolean expression $C\land I$ is true and successfully executing some code called $\mathrm {body}$ , the machine ends up in a state in which I is true.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] If this relation can be proven, the rule then allows us to conclude that successful execution of the program ${\mathtt {while}}\ (C)\ \mathrm {body}$ will lead from a state in which I is true to a state in which $\lnot C\land I$ holds.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The Boolean formula I in this rule is called a loop invariant.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] With some variations in the notation used, and with the premise that the loop halts, this rule is also known as the **Invariant Relation Theorem**.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Let the notation `P { seq } Q` mean that if `P` is true before the sequence of statements `seq` runs, then `Q` is true after it.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The following example illustrates how this rule works.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The condition *C* of the `while` loop is $x<10$ .
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] A useful loop invariant I has to be guessed; it will turn out that $x\leq 10$ is appropriate.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] While this triple can be derived formally from the rules of Floyd-Hoare logic governing assignment, it is also intuitively justified: Computation starts in a state where $x<10\land x\leq 10$ is true, which means simply that $x<10$ is true.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The computation adds 1 to x, which means that $x\leq 10$ is still true (for integer x).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] However, the post-condition $\lnot (x<10)\land x\leq 10$ (x is less than or equal to 10, but it is not less than 10) is logically equivalent to $x=10$ , which is what we wanted to show.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The property $0\leq x$ is another invariant of the example loop, and the trivial property $\mathrm {true}$ is another one.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Applying the above inference rule to the former invariant yields $\{0\leq x\}\;{\mathtt {while}}\ (x<10)\ x:=x+1\;\{10\leq x\}$ .
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Applying it to invariant $\mathrm {true}$ yields $\{\mathrm {true} \}\;{\mathtt {while}}\ (x<10)\ x:=x+1\;\{10\leq x\}$ , which is slightly more expressive.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The Eiffel programming language provides native support for loop invariants.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] A loop invariant is expressed with the same syntax used for a class invariant.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] In the sample below, the loop invariant expression `x <= 10` must be true following the loop initialization, and after each execution of the loop body; this is checked at runtime.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The Whiley programming language also provides first-class support for loop invariants.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The `max()` function determines the largest element in an integer array.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] For this to be defined, the array must contain at least one element.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The postconditions of `max()` require that the returned value is: (1) not smaller than any element; and, (2) that it matches at least one element.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The loop invariant is defined inductively through two `where` clauses, each of which corresponds to a clause in the postcondition.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The fundamental difference is that each clause of the loop invariant identifies the result as being correct up to the current element `i`, whilst the postconditions identify the result as being correct for all elements.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] For 1., a natural language comment (like `// m equals the maximum value in a[0...i-1]` in the above example) is sufficient.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] For 2., programming language support is required, such as the C library assert.h, or the above-shown `invariant` clause in Eiffel.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Often, run-time checking can be switched on (for debugging runs) and off (for production runs) by a compiler or a runtime option.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] For 3., some tools exist to support mathematical proofs, usually based on the above-shown Floyd–Hoare rule, that a given loop code in fact satisfies a given (set of) loop invariant(s).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] The technique of abstract interpretation can be used to detect loop invariants of given code automatically.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] However, this approach is limited to very simple invariants (such as `0<=i && i<=n && i%2==0`).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] In contrast, e.g., the property `0<=i && i<=n` is a loop invariant for both the original and the optimized program, but is not part of the code, hence it doesn't make sense to speak of "moving it out of the loop".
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] Loop-invariant code may induce a corresponding loop-invariant property.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/loop-invariant] A loop-invariant property of this code is `(x1==x2 && t1==x2*x2) || i==0`, indicating that the values computed before the loop agree with those computed within (except before the first iteration).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Moreover, predicate transformer semantics are a reformulation of Floyd–Hoare logic.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Whereas Hoare logic is presented as a deductive system, predicate transformer semantics (either by **weakest-preconditions** or by **strongest-postconditions** see below) are **complete strategies** to build valid deductions of Hoare logic.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] In other words, they provide an effective algorithm to reduce the problem of verifying a Hoare triple to the problem of proving a first-order formula.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Technically, predicate transformer semantics perform a kind of symbolic execution of statements into predicates: execution runs *backward* in the case of weakest-preconditions, or runs *forward* in the case of strongest-postconditions.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] For a statement *S* and a postcondition *R*, a **weakest precondition** is a predicate *Q* such that for any precondition P, $\{P\}S\{R\}$ if and only if $P\Rightarrow Q$ .
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] In other words, it is the "loosest" or least restrictive requirement needed to guarantee that *R* holds after *S*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Uniqueness follows easily from the definition: If both *Q* and *Q'* are weakest preconditions, then by the definition $\{Q'\}S\{R\}$ so $Q'\Rightarrow Q$ and $\{Q\}S\{R\}$ so $Q\Rightarrow Q'$ , and thus $Q=Q'$ .
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] We often use $wp(S,R)$ to denote the weakest precondition for statement *S* with respect to a postcondition *R*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] We use *T* to denote the predicate that is everywhere true and *F* to denote the one that is everywhere false.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] We shouldn't at least conceptually confuse ourselves with a Boolean expression defined by some language syntax, which might also contain true and false as Boolean scalars.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] For such scalars we need to do a type coercion such that we have T = predicate(true) and F = predicate(false).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Such a promotion is carried out often casually, so people tend to take T as true and F as false.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] We give below two equivalent weakest-preconditions for the assignment statement.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] In these formulas, $R[x\leftarrow E]$ is a copy of *R* where free occurrences of *x* are replaced by *E*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Hence, here, expression *E* is implicitly coerced into a *valid term* of the underlying logic: it is thus a *pure* expression, totally defined, terminating and without side effect.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Provided that *E* is well defined, we apply the so-called *one-point* rule on version 1.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The first version avoids a potential duplication of *x* in *R*, whereas the second version is simpler when there is at most a single occurrence of *x* in *R*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The first version also reveals a deep duality between weakest-precondition and strongest-postcondition (see below).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This means that, for the postcondition *x > 10* to be true after the assignment, the precondition *x > 15* must be true before the assignment.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is also the "weakest precondition", in that it is the "weakest" restriction on the value of *x* which makes *x > 10* true after the assignment.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] To show total correctness, we also have to show that the loop terminates.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] However, the conjunction of those three is not a necessary condition.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Actually, Dijkstra's Guarded Command Language (GCL) is an extension of the simple imperative language given until here with non-deterministic statements.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Indeed, GCL aims to be a formal notation to define algorithms.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Non-deterministic statements represent choices left to the actual implementation (in an effective programming language): properties proved on non-deterministic statements are ensured for all possible choices of implementation.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The definitions of weakest-precondition given above (in particular for **while-loop**) preserve this property.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Here, when two guards $E_{i}$ and $E_{j}$ are simultaneously true, then execution of this statement can run any of the associated statement $S_{i}$ or $S_{j}$ .
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Repetition is a generalization of **while** statement in a similar way.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Refinement calculus extends GCL with the notion of *specification statement*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] which specifies a computation that starts in a state satisfying *pre* and is guaranteed to end in a state satisfying *post* by changing only *x*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] We call l a logical constant employed to aid in a specification.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Another example is a computation of a square root of an integer.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The specification statement appears like a primitive in the sense that it does not contain other statements.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] However, it is very expressive, as *pre* and *post* are arbitrary predicates.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] It combines Morgan's syntactic idea with the sharpness idea by Bijlsma, Matthews and Wiltink.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The very advantage of this is its capability of defining wp of goto L and other jump statements.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Formalization of jump statements like *goto L* takes a very long bumpy process.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] A common belief seems to indicate the goto statement could only be argued operationally.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is probably due to a failure to recognize that *goto L* is actually miraculous (i.e. non-strict) and does not follow Dijkstra's coined Law of Miracle Excluded, as stood in itself.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] But it enjoys an extremely simple operational view from the weakest precondition perspective, which was unexpected.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] For *goto L* execution transfers control to label *L* at which the weakest precondition must hold.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The way that *wpL* is referred to in the rule should not be taken as a big surprise.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] It is only ⁠ $wp(L:S,Q)$ ⁠ for some *Q* computed to that point.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is like any wp rules, using constituent statements to give wp definitions, even though *goto L* appears a primitive.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The rule does not require the uniqueness for locations where *wpL* holds within a program, so theoretically it allows the same label to appear in multiple locations as long as the weakest precondition at each location is the same wpL.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The goto statement can jump to any of such locations.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This actually justifies that we could place the same labels at the same location multiple times, as ⁠ $S(L:L:S1)$ ⁠, which is the same as ⁠ $S(L:S1)$ ⁠.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Also, it does not imply any scoping rule, thus allowing a jump into a loop body, for example.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Let us calculate wp of the following program S, which has a jump into the loop body.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] An important variant of the weakest precondition is the **weakest liberal precondition** $wlp(S,R)$ , which yields the weakest condition under which *S* either does not terminate or establishes *R*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] It therefore differs from *wp* in not guaranteeing termination.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Hence it corresponds to Hoare logic in partial correctness: for the statement language given above, *wlp* differs with *wp* only on **while-loop**, in not requiring a variant (see above).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Given *S* a statement and *R* a precondition (a predicate on the initial state), then $sp(S,R)$ is their **strongest-postcondition**: it implies any postcondition satisfied by the final state of any execution of S, for any initial state satisfying R.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Usually, **strongest-postconditions** are used in partial correctness.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Above, the logical variable *y* represents the initial value of variable *x*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Leslie Lamport has suggested *win* and *sin* as *predicate transformers* for concurrent programming.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This section presents some characteristic properties of predicate transformers.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Below, *S* denotes a predicate transformer (a function between two predicates on the state space) and *P* a predicate.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] We keep *x* as the variable of the state space.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Predicate transformers of interest (*wp*, *wlp*, and *sp*) are monotonic.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This property is related to the consequence rule of Hoare logic.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] For instance, *wp* is artificially made strict, whereas *wlp* is generally not.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] In particular, if statement *S* may not terminate then $wlp(S,{\texttt {F}})$ is satisfiable.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Indeed, **T** is a valid invariant of that loop.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] The non-strict but monotonic or conjunctive predicate transformers are called miraculous and can also be used to define a class of programming constructs, in particular, jump statements, which Dijkstra cared less about.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Those jump statements include straight goto L, break and continue in a loop and return statements in a procedure body, exception handling, etc.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] It turns out that all jump statements are executable miracles, i.e. they can be implemented but not strict.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Actually, this terminology makes sense only for strict predicate transformers: indeed, $wp(S,{\texttt {T}})$ is the weakest-precondition ensuring termination of *S*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] It seems that naming this property **non-aborting** would be more appropriate: in total correctness, non-termination is abortion, whereas in partial correctness, it is not.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is the case for $wp(S,.)$ , even if statement *S* is non-deterministic as a selection statement or a specification statement.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This is generally not the case of $wp(S,.)$ when *S* is non-deterministic.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Indeed, consider a non-deterministic statement *S* choosing an arbitrary Boolean.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Then, $wp(S,R)$ reduces to the formula $R[x\leftarrow 0]\wedge R[x\leftarrow 1]$ .
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] In predicate transformers semantics, expressions are restricted to terms of the logic (see above).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] However, this restriction seems too strong for most existing programming languages, where expressions may have side effects (call to a function having a side effect), may not terminate or abort (like *division by zero*).
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] There are many proposals to extend weakest-preconditions or strongest-postconditions for imperative expression languages and in particular for monads.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] Among them, *Hoare Type Theory* combines Hoare logic for a Haskell-like language, separation logic and type theory.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] This system is implemented as a Rocq library named *Ynot*.
[src:axiomatic-semantics/predicate-transformer-semantics] In this language, evaluation of expressions corresponds to computations of *strongest-postconditions*.
